--## 2026-06-21 — Persona Scaffolding and Orchestrator Constraint
--
--### Date
--2026-06-21
--
--### Source
--`#provenance: root/BUILD_LOG.md`
--
--### Decision
--Define the persona topology (Orchestrator + 4 specialists) with strict role boundaries. The Orchestrator must be explicitly constrained to a routing-only role.
--
--### Reasoning
--Early testing revealed the Orchestrator would perform its own research "just to check" after delegating to a specialist — causing duplicate work and contradictory results. The root cause was that the Orchestrator's prompt didn't explicitly prohibit it from performing domain work. It had "you can delegate to specialists" alongside "you have general knowledge," and it defaulted to doing both.
--
--### Changes Made
--- Drafted initial routing logic in the Orchestrator's memory
--- Created a test workflow: "Research Nvidia, analyze its financial health, write a summary report"
--- Updated the Orchestrator's core memory with the hard constraint:
--
--```
--You are a ROUTING SUPERVISOR only. Never perform domain work yourself.
--If a task falls within a persona's domain, delegate it.
--Your job: decompose, delegate, validate, compose — not execute.
--```
--
--- Decided on synchronous delegation for v0.1 (simplicity, debuggability). Parallel delegation deferred to v0.3.
--- Established request-ID namespacing convention (`/root/workdir/req-{id}/`) for passing artifacts between personas via the shared filesystem
--
--### Lessons Learned
--- **The Orchestrator must be explicitly constrained.** Without "You are a ROUTER, not a DOER" in its prompt, it encroaches on persona domains and creates chaos.
--- **Synchronous delegation is slower but debuggable.** This was the right call for v0.1.
--- **Shared filesystem works fine with naming conventions.** People worry about collisions, but request-ID namespacing avoids them reliably.
--
--### Follow-Up Actions
--- Design parallel delegation mechanism for v0.3
--- Expand test workflow to cover more complex multi-step scenarios
--- Document the filesystem convention in ARCHITECTURE.md
--
