--## 2026-06-21 — Shared Filesystem Convention
--
--### Date
--2026-06-21
--
--### Source
--`#provenance: root/BUILD_LOG.md` (Decision D006)
--
--### Decision
--Use a shared filesystem with request-ID namespacing for passing artifacts between personas, rather than SCP, network transfer, or message-context passing.
--
--### Reasoning
--Passing large artifacts through message context failed — context windows filled up, and persona responses became unusably long. Network-based transfer (SCP) was over-engineered for same-machine operation. A shared filesystem with a simple naming convention (`/root/workdir/req-{id}/`) provides reliable, zero-latency artifact passing.
--
--### Changes Made
--- Established the `/root/workdir/req-{id}/` naming convention
--- Each delegated subtask writes its output to its request-specific directory
--- The Orchestrator reads the output from the filesystem after the persona completes
--- Risk of collision is mitigated by unique request IDs
--
--### Lessons Learned
--- **Don't over-engineer the transport layer.** Files are fine when the system runs on a single machine.
--- Request-ID namespacing is simple, transparent, and debuggable — anyone can `ls /root/workdir/` to see active tasks.
--- This pattern would need revisiting if personas ever run on separate machines (containerized per-persona is a future goal).
--
--### Follow-Up Actions
--- Consider formalizing a cleanup policy for old request directories
--- Document the convention in the Operations Manager's procedures
