--## 2026-06-23 — Repository Initialization
--
--### Date
--2026-06-23
--
--### Source
--`#provenance: repos/build-log.md`
--
--### Decision
--Create `agent-env-selfhosted` as the single source of truth for platform documentation, configuration, and operational procedures.
--
--### Reasoning
--The platform was operating with no persistent documentation outside the Hermes agent's ephemeral memory and conversation history. When the agent is reset or a session is closed, infrastructure decisions are lost. A GitHub repository provides:
--- Version-controlled documentation that survives container rebuilds
--- A structured reference for future maintainers
--- A pattern for the agent to document its own platform (dogfooding)
--
--### Changes Made
--- Created the `agent-env-selfhosted` GitHub repository
--- Established the repository boundary: documentation and *definitions* go in, runtime *state* stays out
--- Set up `.gitignore` to block secrets, credentials, caches, logs, runtime memory, vector stores, and build artifacts
--- Created directory structure: `docs/`, `agent/`, `workspaces/`, `logs/`
--- Populated placeholder documentation files (header-only)
--
--### Lessons Learned
--- The repository boundary must be clearly defined from day one — retroactively removing committed secrets is difficult
--- The `.gitignore` must be aggressive from the start — `.env`, `secrets.env`, `*.log`, and `__pycache__` patterns should be blocked by default
--- Memory protection rules (no runtime memory, no embeddings, no conversation history) must be enforced at commit time
--- `.gitkeep` files are necessary to preserve empty directory structure in Git
--
--### Follow-Up Actions
--- Add a pre-commit hook or CI check to verify no secrets are accidentally committed
--- Consider a `.gitattributes` file for language-appropriate diff settings on documentation files
--
