--## 2026-06-23 — Security-First Repository Structure
--
--### Date
--2026-06-23
--
--### Source
--`#provenance: repos/build-log.md`
--
--### Decision
--Scaffold the repository with a strict `.gitignore`, placeholder documentation only, and no substantive code in the first commit.
--
--### Reasoning
--Repository security is easier to establish on day one than to retrofit. The first commit establishes:
--- A comprehensive `.gitignore` organized by category (Secrets, Cache, Environments, Build Artifacts) for maintainability
--- A directory structure that separates documentation (`docs/`), definitions (`agent/`), and runtime state (`workspaces/`, `logs/`)
--- Placeholder documentation files (header-only) that will be populated in subsequent commits
--
--### Changes Made
--- Created categorized `.gitignore` sections
--- Established `docs/`, `agent/`, `workspaces/`, `logs/` directory structure
--- Added `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`, `docs/CONFIGURATION.md`, `docs/DEPLOYMENT.md`, `docs/OPERATIONS.md`, `docs/SECURITY.md` as header-only placeholders
--- Added `agent/memory/` and `agent/personas/` with definition templates
--- Pre-populated `.gitkeep` files in directories that would otherwise be empty
--
--### Lessons Learned
--- `.gitignore` sections should be organized by category for maintainability — when a new category needs an exclusion, it goes in the right section
--- Even placeholder `.md` files should have clear comments indicating their intended content
--- Directory structure must reflect the separation of concerns: definitions ≠ runtime state ≠ documentation
--
--### Follow-Up Actions
--- Monitor for files that should be in `.gitignore` but aren't yet
--- Consider adding a `.gitignore` validation step to the CI pipeline
