--## 2026-06-23 — Dedicated GitHub Automation Account
--
--### Date
--2026-06-23
--
--### Source
--`#provenance: repos/build-log.md`
--
--### Decision
--Create a dedicated GitHub account (`johnalencar-agent`) for all automated Git operations, rather than using the personal account's credentials.
--
--### Reasoning
--1. **Blast radius:** A leaked PAT (Personal Access Token) on the agent account only compromises repository access, not personal account access
--2. **Auditability:** Commits from the automation account are clearly distinguishable from human commits
--3. **Credential lifecycle:** The automation token can be rotated without affecting personal access
--4. **Scope limitation:** The automation account has `repo` scope access only to the `agent-env-selfhosted` repository
--
--### Changes Made
--- Created `johnalencar-agent` GitHub account
--- Generated a fine-grained PAT (organization-level) for better scope control than classic PATs
--- Stored the token in the local `secrets.env` file, outside the repository and session database
--- Configured `git config user.email` using the `users.noreply.github.com` format for the automation account
--
--### Lessons Learned
--- Fine-grained PATs provide better scope control than classic PATs
--- The token must never enter the repository, the session database, or the Hermes conversation history
--- A dedicated automation account makes it trivial to distinguish "agent committed this" from "human committed this" in Git history
--
--### Follow-Up Actions
--- Document the PAT rotation procedure in SECURITY.md
--- Set up calendar reminder for PAT expiry/renewal
--
