--# Cross-Cutting: Lessons Learned
--
--These are cumulative lessons extracted from all entries above.
--
--## Lesson 1: Name Things By Their Boundary, Not Their Prestige
--
--"Software Engineer" sounds better than "Dev" in a resume. But in the system, clarity > prestige. The persona name should define a clear, non-overlapping boundary. If two personas could plausibly handle the same task, the naming is wrong.
--
--## Lesson 2: Memory Is Not Optional
--
--A persona without seeded memory is not a persona — it's a blank LLM with a label. The memory is what makes it an expert. Invest time in writing good core memory files. They're the difference between a system that works and a system that requires constant hand-holding.
--
--## Lesson 3: The Orchestrator Must Be Constrained
--
--The Orchestrator naturally wants to do everything. It's the main point of contact, it has the broadest context, and it has access to all the same tools. Without explicit constraints ("You are a ROUTER, not a DOER"), it will encroach on persona domains and create chaos.
--
--## Lesson 4: Validate Early, Validate Often
--
--Our first pass had no validation. The second pass had format-only validation. The third pass added content validation. We should have started with content validation from day one. A persona returning garbage 20% of the time is a system that fails 20% of the time.
--
--## Lesson 5: Document While It's Fresh
--
--Write the log as you go, not after the fact. This Engineering Journal exists because we forgot why we made a decision two days after making it.
--
--## Lesson 6: Shared Filesystem Is Fine With Conventions
--
--People worry about filesystem collisions, but with a simple request-ID namespacing convention, it works perfectly. Don't over-engineer the transport layer. Files are fine.
--
--## Lesson 7: Personas Are Not Blank Slates
--
--Seed persona memory before the first interaction. Starting with empty memory forces re-explanation of each persona's job every session.
--
--## Lesson 8: Default Security Is Rarely Sufficient
--
--Default profile configs, default Docker isolation, and default `.gitignore` patterns all fell short. Each required explicit hardening. Defaults are starting points, not endpoints.
--
--## Lesson 9: ARM Is Production-Ready for Agent Workloads
--
--Network-bound and I/O-bound workloads perform identically on ARM. The main limitation (Docker image availability) was sidestepped by the LXD-based architecture.
--
--## Lesson 10: Outbound-Only Is the Safest Network Default
--
--No inbound ports means no attack surface. The operational cost (requiring host SSH for container access) is acceptable for single-operator deployment.
--
-----
--
--# Cross-Cutting: What We'd Do Differently
--
--If we were starting over (or planning a v2.0):
--
--1. **Containerize each persona.** Running each profile in a Docker container (or at least a separate user) would provide filesystem-level isolation in addition to profile-level isolation. Currently, any persona can read any other persona's memory files (though convention says they shouldn't).
--
--2. **Start with intent-based routing.** Keyword matching was a dead end. We should have invested in intent classification from the start.
--
--3. **Write validation criteria simultaneously with routing rules.** They're two sides of the same coin. Writing them separately meant we had routing without validation for too long.
--
--4. **Test with adversarial inputs.** We tested with "normal" requests. We didn't test with confusing, ambiguous, or malicious requests until late in development. Adversarial testing would have caught the routing fuzzy-match issue earlier.
--
--5. **Version control the profiles.** Currently, profile configs and memories live in `~/.hermes/profiles/` and are not version-controlled. If someone accidentally deletes a core memory file, there's no way to restore it (except memory). We should at least have a git repo for the profiles directory.
--
--6. **Use fine-grained PATs from day one.** Classic PATs offer all-or-nothing scoping. Fine-grained PATs allow repository-level permissions. This should be the default for any automation account.
--
--7. **Establish the Engineering Journal from day one.** The first build log entry was written on 2026-06-23, three days after the project started. Three days of decisions — including why Hermes was chosen, why profiles were structured a certain way, and early test failures — were lost.
